<p><a NAME="1. Substructure in Wide-Angle Tailed  (WAT) Clusters."></a><font size=+1>1.
Substructure in Clusters with Radio Galaxies.</font>
<br>&nbsp;
<blockquote>My interest in radio galaxies in clusters stems from my dissertation
work at NMSU.&nbsp; Radio galaxies like <a href="./watdef.html">WATs</a>&nbsp;
make usefull probes of cluster evolution. Although they are created on very
small scales in AGN, their diffuse tails
extend far into the intracluster medium (ICM) and are presumably shaped
and confined by this hot gas.
<p>X-ray imaging for my dissertation confirmed that extended X-ray emission
exists around WATs.  The X-ray isophotes also show elongations correlating
with the radio tails.
<p>My redshift survey (in press) has shown that the host galaxies of
WATs are nearly at rest with respect to their
subcluster.&nbsp; It also shows that the host clusters of WATs do not
show a significantly higher occurence of substructure.
<p>I am continuing to gather data to discern whether the clusters containing
WATs show systematically more substructure than other clusters.&nbsp; This
might be expected if the bending of the WATs is caused by winds generated
in mergers.&nbsp; Another popular hypothesis is that the winds are generated
by infall along supercluster filaments.
