<a NAME="2)  Supermassive Blackholes and evolution of Early-type galaxie"></a>
<br>2)&nbsp; Supermassive Blackholes and evolution of Early-type galaxies.
<br>&nbsp;
<blockquote>My current postdoc with Doug Richstone involves work with 
Space Telescope Imaging Spectrograph (STIS) data of nearby galaxies.&nbsp;
I have reduced the Cycle 7 data and presented them at the Jan and June
2000 AAS meetings.&nbsp; These spectra were of nearby early-type galaxies 
(E and S0's). The CaII stellar absorption lines are used to measure the stars
losvd's (line-of-sight velocity distributions) for these galaxies. The
first two moments of the losvds are shown below. The NGC numbers are in
green.
<p>The losvd's for these galaxies were analyzed to constrain the orbital
motions of the stars which, in turn, revealed the masses of the central
black holes.  The black hole masses for our 10 galaxies significantly 
contributed to a growing database used to understand the demographics of
supermassive black holes.  It led our team to discover the tight correlation 
between black hole mass and global velocity dispersion (Gebhardt et al. 2000).
</p>
